================================================================================

Section 1:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST SPECIAL SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1561
H.P. 1019 House of Representatives, April 10, 2025
Licensee's Lobster Traps That May Be Fished in a Lobster
Management Zone Listed on the License as a Secondary Zone
Reference to the Committee on Marine Resources suggested and ordered printed.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative HEPLER of Woolwich.
Cosponsored by Senator MOORE of Washington and
Representatives: EATON of Deer Isle, FAULKINGHAM of Winter Harbor, STOVER of
Boothbay, Senator: TEPLER of Sagadahoc.
Printed on recycled paper
1 Sec. 1. Definitions. Resolved: That for the purposes of this resolve, unless the
2 context indicates otherwise, the following terms have the following meanings.
3 1. "Department" means the Department of Marine Resources.
4 2. "Lobster management policy council" or "council" means a council established
5 pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 12, section 6447, subsection 1.
6 3. "Secondary zone" means a lobster management zone listed on a lobster and crab
7 fishing license, in accordance with the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 12, section 6446,
8 subsection 1-A, as a zone in which the licensee intends to fish some, but not the majority,
9 of the licensee's lobster traps.
10 Sec. 2. Input from lobster management policy councils; report. Resolved:
11 That the department shall seek input from the lobster management policy councils to obtain
12 feedback regarding what percentage of a lobster and crab fishing licensee's lobster traps a
13 licensee may fish in a secondary zone. The department shall develop recommendations
14 regarding the percentage based on the input received from the councils. By December 3,
15 2025, the department shall submit to the Joint Standing Committee on Marine Resources a
16 report that includes the department's recommendations. The committee may submit
17 legislation related to the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
18 SUMMARY
1199 This resolve directs the Department of Marine Resources to seek input from the lobster
2200 management policy councils to obtain feedback regarding what percentage of a lobster and
2211 crab fishing licensee's lobster traps a licensee may fish in a lobster management zone that
2222 is listed on the licensee's license as a zone in which the licensee intends to fish some lobster
2233 traps, but is not designated as the zone in which the licensee intends to fish the majority of
2244 the licensee's lobster traps, also known as a secondary zone. The department must use the
2255 input received from the councils to develop recommendations regarding the percentage of
2266 traps that may be fished in a secondary zone. The department must submit a report,
2277 including its recommendations, to the Joint Standing Committee on Marine Resources no
2288 later than December 3, 2025. The committee is authorized to submit legislation related to
2299 the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
